	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EU–Thailand FTA negotiations: Tuna stakes</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 October 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Negotiations for an EU–Thailand free trade agreement (FTA) have resumed. In this context, the president of the Thai Tuna Industry Association backs Thailand’s request for unlimited quantities of duty-free tuna exports to the EU canned tuna market. He emphasised that “with the current 24% duty stamped on Thai exports to the EU, other countries such as Papua New Guinea with 0% duty form unfair competition for the Thai canners.” Currently, the EU market absorbs 10% of Thai canned tuna exports – in 2012, Thailand exported almost 560,000 tonnes of canned tuna and pre-cooked loins to the EU.</p><p>The Spanish tuna industry, however, wants tuna to be left out of the negotiations, considering it a “sensitive product”. This highlights the risk of competition involved in granting tariff concessions to the world’s leading canned tuna-producing nation. It also raises issues of child labour and poor working conditions in tuna canneries and on-board Thai fishing vessels. This assertion was somewhat confirmed by recent International Labour Organization (ILO) research, which showed that the Thai fishing industry fails to meet both domestic and international labour standards – up to 16% of the interviewed fishers employed on Thai long-distance fishing fleets said that they had not entered the industry of their own free will; that children under 15 years were working on these vessels; and that 94% of the workers surveyed did not have written work contracts.</p><p>EU and Thai officials warned Thai tuna canners that they should urgently improve their production standards. Thailand is expected to withdraw completely from the EU Generalised System of Preferences (GSP) in 2015, being an ‘upper income’ country, but once signed, the FTA should help compensate for the loss of GSP privileges.</p><p>The Thai tuna industry is taking steps to address these criticisms. At a recent tuna conference in Spain, representatives of the Thai tuna sector refuted claims that they would try to monopolise the EU canned tuna market once Thailand had obtained 0% duty, and stressed that such tariff concessions were needed “to deal with competition from other countries such as Papua New Guinea and the Philippines”. Moreover, the Thai Union Frozen Products (TUF) – the world’s leading seafood processor and exporter – announced that it is joining the ILO ‘Good Labour Practices’ programme. In so doing, TUF vows to respect the 10 binding principles of the programme and to openly report how its business adheres to globally recognised ethical standards. The ILO director for Thailand said: “It is encouraging to see that a Thai-based global brand like TUF openly supports good labour practices and will work with our organisation to improve the industry standards in Thailand.”</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Atuna.com</i>, ‘Thai processors told to gear up for FTA with EU’, 11&nbsp;September 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13378" target="_self">http://www.atuna.com/apps/public/ViewArticle.asp?ID=13378</a></p><p>ILO, ‘Good labour practices programme for addressing child labour and forced labour in Thai fisheries industry launched’, 17&nbsp;September 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ilo.org/asia/info/public/newsitems/WCMS_221563/lang--en/index.htm" target="_self">http://www.ilo.org/asia/info/public/newsitems/WCMS_221563/lang--en/index...</a></p><p><i>Europapress.es</i>, ‘La Xunta pide “unión de esfuerzos” para defender un “mercado único e igualitario” del atún’, 9&nbsp;September 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.europapress.es/galicia/pesca-00247/noticia-pesca-xunta-pide-union-esfuerzos-defender-mercado-unico-igualitario-atun-20130909134430.html" target="_self">http://www.europapress.es/galicia/pesca-00247/noticia-pesca-xunta-pide-u...</a></p><p>ILO, ‘ILO study examines working conditions in Thai fishing industry, 2&nbsp;September 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ilo.org/asia/info/public/pr/WCMS_220597/lang--en/index.htm" target="_self">http://www.ilo.org/asia/info/public/pr/WCMS_220597/lang--en/index.htm</a></p><p>FFA, ‘Market and industry dynamics in the global tuna supply chain’, by Hamilton et al., June 2011</p><p>http://www.academia.edu/1281111/Hamilton_et_al_2011_Market_and_Industry_Dynamics_in_the_Global_Tuna_Supply_Chain</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Thai stakeholders are actively arguing for duty-free quota-free access to EU markets for their tuna products and, therefore, for the erosion of ACP preferences for tuna products. With Thailand’s comparative advantages (e.g. good access to raw material, economies of scale in processing), it is unlikely that Thai products would be threatened by ACP countries exporting tuna to EU markets. On the contrary, ACP countries’ tuna exports to the EU could be seriously affected if such concessions were given to Thailand through the future FTA, as highlighted in a study on market and industry dynamics in the global tuna supply chain. In this case, it would seem that ACP tuna-producing countries have similar interests to those expressed by the EU sector: that tuna should be treated as a ‘sensitive product’ in the FTA negotiations; and that Thai tuna exports to the EU should not be at the cost of social and environmental dumping.</p>
		</div>
		
